(601, 1, '2018-09-05 15:45:24', '2018-09-05 15:45:24', '<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Mallam Bashir Mamman, the NTI Director of Examinations, has been granted approval to oversee the affairs of the Institute as the Acting Director-General and Chief Executive on behalf of Prof. Garba Dahuwa Azare, who would be proceeding on the balance of his 2018 Annual Leave effective August 13, 2018. The disclosure was made through a circular to NTI staff at headquarters, zonal and state offices, titled:<strong> ``Absence from duty of the Director-General and Chief</strong> <strong>Executive</strong> <strong>and Acting Registrar,’’</strong>  released on Monday, July 30, 2018 from the NTI Registry  Department and signed by Mr Obioha Ogbuka.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">It also indicated that Mallam Mohammed Abubakar Sadiq, the NTI Deputy Registrar, Academic Records Division (ARD) would oversee the affairs of the Institute’s Registry Department effective from, Wednesday, August 1, 2018, on behalf of Mallam Mahmud Muhammed Usman, the Registrar, who would proceed on his 2018 Annual Leave from that day.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">``Kindly note and cooperate with the officers in the performance of their assigned duties,’’ Ogbuka concluded.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">      PHOTO   SPEAK</p>\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-650\" src=\"http://www.nti.edu.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/14-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" />Ag. Director Quality Assurance and ICT, Mal. Ibrahim Mohammed Aminu, Prof. Muhammad Yakasai of BUK with other academics and Retirees deliberating on quality assurance instruments, recently.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-651\" src=\"http://www.nti.edu.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/15-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" />Prof. Sagir Adamu Abbas of EDUCONSERV making a formal presentation of NTI Strategic Plan and other documents produced by the firm to the DG/CE of NTI, Prof. Garba Dahuwa Azare, recently.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-652\" src=\"http://www.nti.edu.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/16-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" />\n\nNTI staff during the workshop on computer software application and web development tools, recently.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-653\" src=\"http://www.nti.edu.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/17-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" />The representative of DG/CE and Ag. Director Quality Assurance and ICT, Mal. Ibrahim Mohammed Aminu inaugurating the new ACTU office at the last floor of the Conference Centre.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-654\" src=\"http://www.nti.edu.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/18-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" />Dr. Zainab Shuaibu, head of National Trainers, SMASE, assisting pupils from the NTI Model Primary School, during their visit on familiarising themselves with scientific apparatus, at the centre, recently.\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"></p>', 'STOP PRESS', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'news-media-3', '', '', '2018-09-05 15:45:24', '2018-09-05 15:45:24', '', 0, 'http://www.nti.edu.ng/?p=601', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(609, 1, '2018-09-05 12:25:48', '2018-09-05 12:25:48', '<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>NTI GRADUATES 375, 256 NCE IN 28 YEARS </strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong> <img class=\"size-medium wp-image-602 alignleft\" src=\"http://www.nti.edu.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/1-200x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"200\" height=\"300\" /></strong><strong>Prof. Garba Dahuwa Azare, DG/CE of NTI </strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>No fewer than 375, 256 students graduated from the NTI’s Nigeria Certificate in Education (NCE) in the last 28 years</strong>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Mal. Bashir Mamman, the NTI Director of Examinations, made the disclosure on Tuesday, July 24 at the Directorate Conference Room, while presenting results of the 2017 graduating set of the Institute’s Nigeria Certificate in Education (NCE) at the 4<sup>th</sup> Academic Board Meeting. He said the Board had approved the results of <strong>9,530 </strong>out of the<strong> 17, 385 </strong>students that sat for the 2017 NCE through the Distance Learning System (DLS) Examination.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em><strong>‘’ The set of graduating students presented to Board was admitted in 2014,’’</strong></em> he said.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">The Academic Board of the Institute comprised of the Management staff led by the Director-General and Chief Executive, Six Zonal Coordinators, reputable academics, who are representatives of the Universities of Nigeria, Nsukka, Ibadan and Benin and representatives of Centre Managers. Mamman, who presented the students’ results one subject after another, gave an analysis of each and sought approval before the Board. The analysis showed that those who passed represented 54.82 per cent   in addition to indicating that there was a drop in the number of students that sat for the examination compared with 2016 set, which has 18,415 students with 10,604 passing. During a Power Point presentation of the results, it was shown that the maximum Cumulative Grade Point Average (CGPA) a student could get is 5.00.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Analysis on the states indicated that Kaduna State had 2,198 students out of which 1,143 passed representing 52 per cent, followed by the FCT with a population of 1,762, with 727 passing and representing 41.26 per cent. It further indicated that Bauchi has the least number with 33 students and only 15 passed representing 45.45 per cent and followed by Ekiti state with 47 students that sat for the examination, 33 passed representing 70.21 per cent.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">In the subject by subject analysis, 10,697 out of 10,707 students that sat for Education, representing 99.91 per cent had passed the paper. The report disclosed that 2,355 out of 2,359 sat for English Language representing 99.83 per cent passed. It was revealed that 896 students out of 906 that sat for Integrated Science nationwide representing 98.90 per cent passed the subject. The overall best student of the year 2017 was Ms.  Umar Bara’at, Candidate Number 001129 from Government Secondary School  Mokwa, Study Centre, Niger State. She read PES/Social Studies. Bara’at has a C.G.P.A of 4.66.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">At the meeting, Prof. Garba Dahuwa Azare, the Institute’s Director-General and Chief Executive, who chaired the meeting expressed his satisfaction with the procedure of deliberation by members. Azare said that the Institute is trying to improve on the quality of its services. On the issue of backlog of certificates, he revealed that no fewer than 25,000 certificates are now ready for collection. Azare said that having fulfilled and followed all the due processes, the Usumanu Danfodio University, Sokoto, released the certificates for the Institute. He solicited the support of the representatives of the universities that were present, who are the Deans of Faculties of Education to support and make observations during the meeting.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em><strong>\" We are ready to abide by the observations and corrections,\" </strong></em>he said.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">The meeting observed the dwindling number of enrolment, most especially in subjects like Mathematics, Cultural and Creative Arts and Integrated Science. Responding to the observation raised, Mr. Ndem Ndem, the Acting Director Academic Services, suggested that awareness should be created to avert the situation. Speaking on payment of fees by students, Mr. Yakubu Akaaba Momoh, the Acting Director Field Operations and Students Services said the department through zonal and state offices have sensitized students on registration process and payment, with emphasis to pay school fees in time. The meeting was also attended by Mal. Yunusa Labaran, the Acting Bursar; Mal. Sadiq Abubakar Mohammed, Deputy Registrar, Academic Record Division and Mrs. Fatima Abbas Jega, Deputy Director Test Administration, Examinations Department.</p>', 'NTI GRADUATES 375, 256 NCE IN 28 YEARS', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'news-media-4', '', '', '2018-09-05 12:25:48', '2018-09-05 12:25:48', '', 0, 'http://www.nti.edu.ng/?p=609', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(612, 1, '2018-09-05 12:32:39', '2018-09-05 12:32:39', '<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>NTI MANAGEMENT APPROVES COMPUTERISATION OF REGISTRY DEPARTMENT</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong> </strong>Malam Mahmud Muhammed Usman, the NTI Registrar, has said that the Institute’s Management has approved the computerisation of its Registry Department to electronically back up Pension, Open and Secret Files of all staff nationwide. Usman who disclosed that no fewer than 12 staff with sound ICT background were carefully selected from within the department for the exercise, also said Computers, Scanners and a separate office had been provided for the task.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em><strong>\"The back-up is to be carried out in phases, the first phase will cover the files domiciled at the Open Registry, the second phase will cover files in the Secret Registry and lastly the files in the Pensions and Welfare unit. The exercise is expected to be completed before the end of 2018, after which other phases of the computerization would continue,\"</strong></em> he said.</p>\n</blockquote>', 'NTI MANAGEMENT APPROVES COMPUTERISATION OF REGISTRY DEPARTMENT', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'news-media-5', '', '', '2018-09-05 12:32:39', '2018-09-05 12:32:39', '', 0, 'http://www.nti.edu.ng/?p=612', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(614, 1, '2018-09-05 12:51:58', '2018-09-05 12:51:58', '<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>NTI REGISTRAR ENUMERATES STRATEGIES FOR EXCELLENT SERVICE DELIVERY</strong></p>\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-605 alignleft\" src=\"http://www.nti.edu.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/2-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" />\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Mal. Mahmud Mohammed Usman, NTI Ag. Registrar and Secretary to the Council</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong> </strong>Mal. Mahmud Mohammed Usman, the NTI Registrar, has said that the Institute requires commitment to no fewer than 12 Revenue Enhancement Strategies <strong>(RES)</strong>for excellent service delivery and revitilisation of education in Nigeria. Mal. Usman made the disclosure recently, while presenting a paper titled:<strong> ``<em>SWOT Analysis and</em> <em>Strategies at Enhancing the Revenue Base of NTI, Kaduna-Nigeria,’’ </em></strong><em>co</em>-authored with Mr Obioha Ogbuka, the NTI Deputy Registrar, Human Resources , at the <strong>Management of Higher</strong> <strong>Education Institutes Programme, Galilee International Management Institute(GIMI), Israel.</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">He argued that one of the <strong>RES </strong>included the need to diversify sources of funding of NTI with dwindling government income and the introduction of new programmes both academic and those having to do with capacity building.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong><em>\"Re-orientating management and staff of the Institute in thinking of the Institute as a business and building new capacity on marketing, critical thinking, strategic management and emotional intelligence to transit from being efficient managers to effective leaders.</em> Increase in the number of staff in the core education specialisation for seamlessly implementing the mandate of the institute is recommended,\"</strong> he said.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">According to him, other<strong> RES</strong> included re-admitting the institute into the Tertiary Education Trust Fund and intensification of donor funding at both local and international levels in addition to advocating emphasis on alternative sources of funding. He stressed that building of alumni association and tapping from immense funding opportunities derivable there from while building the relationship between the Institute and her current and future students is one of the 12 <strong>RES. </strong>The Registrar mentioned that another component of his proposed 12 RES includes convincing the government on the necessity for mandatory continuing professional training for teachers like other professions and housing such intervention programme with the Institute.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em><strong>\"Commercialisation of the Institute’s manuals and payment of `token ‘fees for some hitherto free services the institute renders to students and other stakeholders. Sustainability of current prudence in expenditure, cost efficiency in operations and value for money in all transactions, are other strategies,’’</strong></em> he said.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">And argued that otherwise the gains of anticipated boost in revenue might be short-lived.He concluded by advancing that there is no doubt that the Open and Distance Education System had been proven to be cost-effective, viable and qualitative system that is used globally to complement the conventional system of education.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em><strong>\"There is no doubt that the Open and Distance Education System has been proven to be cost-effective, viable and qualitative system that is used globally to complement the conventional system of education,\" </strong></em>says M.M. Usman, NTI Registrar.</p>\n</blockquote>', 'NTI REGISTRAR ENUMERATES STRATEGIES FOR EXCELLENT SERVICE DELIVERY', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'news-media-6', '', '', '2018-09-05 12:51:58', '2018-09-05 12:51:58', '', 0, 'http://www.nti.edu.ng/?p=614', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(617, 1, '2018-09-05 12:57:50', '2018-09-05 12:57:50', '<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>NTI CONDUCTS TEACHING PRACTICE EXERCISE FOR STUDENTS-TEACHERS</strong></p>\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-606 alignleft\" src=\"http://www.nti.edu.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/3-300x214.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"214\" />\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Mr. Yakubu Akaaba Momoh, Ag. Director FOSS</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">The Institute had between June 11 and 15, conducted a nationwide teaching practice exercise in a bid to expose its students to teaching techniques. Mr.Yakubu Akaaba Momoh, the  Director Field Operations and Students Services,(FOSS) told <strong>The Bulletin </strong>that prior to the exercise, a seminar meant for that purpose took place between on May 7  and  11.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">He explained that the exercise was for Cycle Four Students of the Nigeria Certificate in Education (NCE) and 400 level Degree pointing out that the Post-Graduate Diploma in Education(PGDE) students would have their own in October. According to him, the Institute is trying to come to terms with the guidelines of the National Commission for Colleges of Education (NCCE). The Director said teaching practice is a very important exercise that exposes teacher trainees to the practical techniques of the profession. A document on the exercise indicated that the exercise is a very important component of teacher preparation through Distance Learning System by the Institute.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em><b>\"It makes the teacher trainees have a real-life experience of the classroom which exposes them to opportunities of actualising the teaching techniques/methodologies and also practicing the theories of teaching learnt during tutorial contacts\".</b></em></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">According to it, the objectives of the teaching practice monitoring exercise is to ascertain that the students were properly briefed, on the expectations of the teaching practice exercise and ascertain that they are carrying out the exercise and that they are being supervised and moderated as planned. The monitoring officers were expected to discuss and guide student-teachers on areas of strengths and weaknesses, check student’s identity card, evidence of payment, students’ timetable, observe, analyse and give feedback on all teaching practice activities in the state.</p>', 'NTI CONDUCTS TEACHING PRACTICE EXERCISE FOR STUDENTS-TEACHERS', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'news-media-7', '', '', '2018-09-05 12:57:50', '2018-09-05 12:57:50', '', 0, 'http://www.nti.edu.ng/?p=617', 0, 'post', '', 0);
